WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.400
What if I told you that true and false don't actually exist inside your computer?

00:06.580 --> 00:06.880
Right.

00:06.880 --> 00:14.300
That the fundamental logic running your bank account, your phone, the entire internet, it's actually just, well, it's an illusion.

00:14.600 --> 00:20.960
It's this human interface pasted over a geometric web of, you know, raw flowing data.

00:21.220 --> 00:26.100
I mean, it sounds like science fiction or maybe like a philosophical thought experiment.

00:26.340 --> 00:26.500
Yeah.

00:26.500 --> 00:35.000
But the reality of how computation functions at its absolute lowest level is far stranger and frankly, far more fluid than the rigid text we use to program it.

00:35.180 --> 00:40.860
Because we've spent decades, literally decades, forcing machines to think in absolute binaries.

00:41.100 --> 00:43.240
And if you've ever tried coding, you know that pain.

00:43.420 --> 00:49.540
I mean, I spent three days last month just trying to debug this simple Python script that was supposed to automate my email.

00:49.760 --> 00:50.320
Oh, yeah.

00:50.520 --> 00:51.380
That's always fun.

00:51.440 --> 00:51.600
Right.

00:51.680 --> 00:54.680
And the entire thing crashed because of a single missing parenthesis.

00:55.020 --> 00:55.500
Exactly.

00:55.500 --> 00:59.600
You build this rigid architecture, just laying bricks of code line by line.

00:59.800 --> 01:04.520
And if one brick is a millimeter out of place, the compiler just throws a fatal error.

01:04.820 --> 01:06.400
Which is incredibly fragile.

01:06.620 --> 01:11.980
I mean, we've built our entire digital civilization on that text-based, top-down fragility.

01:12.180 --> 01:13.740
Well, welcome to this deep dive.

01:14.240 --> 01:20.480
If you're joining us today, and, you know, as the learner, I know you're here because you love connecting the dots across complex systems.

01:21.040 --> 01:23.900
We are embarking on something incredibly special today.

01:24.000 --> 01:24.660
