03:25.300 --> 03:31.720
But Church was trying to formalize logic using paper and pencil and later, you know, early typewriters.

03:31.720 --> 03:31.940
Sure.

03:31.940 --> 03:36.700
So, by necessity, computation became heavily textual.

03:37.180 --> 03:44.080
It was all about abstraction and application, but represented by sequences of characters and endless nested parentheses.

03:44.440 --> 03:46.080
Because that was the medium of the time.

03:46.160 --> 03:48.280
I mean, you had a typewriter, so you wrote code like a manuscript.

03:48.480 --> 03:48.580
Yeah.

03:48.680 --> 03:49.920
You literally couldn't do it any other way.

03:50.000 --> 03:50.240
Right.

03:50.360 --> 03:59.540
But the spherepop calculus, or SPC as they abbreviate it, argues that this textual limitation fundamentally bottlenecked our understanding of computation.

03:59.840 --> 04:00.160
Oh, so.

04:00.160 --> 04:05.400
It takes the lambda calculus and transforms it from a flat line of text into three-dimensional geometry.

04:05.400 --> 04:11.000
Okay, so instead of hitting the bracket key on my keyboard to open a function, I'm dealing with something physical.

04:11.220 --> 04:11.320
Yeah.

04:11.320 --> 04:12.900
And interacting with geometric scopes.

04:13.040 --> 04:13.520
Exactly.

04:14.080 --> 04:16.240
The paper introduces two core primitives.

04:16.240 --> 04:17.600
The first is the sphere.

04:18.000 --> 04:20.060
Think of the sphere as the act of abstraction.

04:20.600 --> 04:26.680
You are drawing a physical geometric boundary around a space of computation, basically entering a bubble.

04:26.820 --> 04:27.780
Okay, let's unpack this.

04:27.780 --> 04:33.260
It's like, okay, think about exploring a map in a massive open world video game.

04:33.340 --> 04:33.600
Sure.

04:33.900 --> 04:34.120
Yeah.

04:34.380 --> 04:38.480
A sphere would be like unlocking a new dungeon.

04:39.020 --> 04:44.880
That specific rune has its own physical rules, its own isolated environment, its own inventory, right?

04:45.320 --> 04:47.800
Entering it is an extraction from the main world map.

04:47.800 --> 04:48.900
That's a great way to look at it.

04:49.040 --> 04:50.560
And the second primitive is the pop.

04:50.880 --> 04:56.240
If the sphere is abstraction, the pop is application, or what mathematicians would call beta reduction.

04:56.540 --> 04:56.760
Okay.

04:56.760 --> 05:01.860
It is the act of collapsing that sphere with a specific argument to produce a result.

05:01.860 --> 05:20.680
So, carrying the video game analogy forward, popping would be like detonating a highly specific required item, like, I don't know, a skeleton key or bomb inside that dungeon, which instantly collapses the entire room into a single piece of usable data, like loot, that you carry back out into the main world.

05:20.680 --> 05:29.820
The visual is strikingly accurate, actually, and in the spherepop domain-specific language, the DSL, you actually author these geometric scenes.

05:30.040 --> 05:32.740
Programmers aren't writing traditional lines of code anymore.

05:32.840 --> 05:33.500
What are they doing instead?

05:33.720 --> 05:42.040
They're using spatial commands, things like at scene, sphere, pop, and burst, to choreograph a geometric event.

05:42.600 --> 05:46.320
The authors describe this computationally as a coherence foam.

05:46.440 --> 05:47.620
Coherence foam, okay.

05:47.620 --> 05:55.540
And in categorical math terms, they represent sphere and pop as the exponential and evaluation morphisms within a pre-chief topos.

05:55.720 --> 05:56.680
Whoa, whoa, hold on.

05:56.740 --> 06:00.960
We promised the listener we'd leave the heavy jargon at the door, or at least, you know, translate it.

06:01.080 --> 06:02.700
What on earth is a pre-chief topos?

06:02.840 --> 06:03.720
Fair enough, fair enough.

06:03.840 --> 06:09.160
Okay, a topos is essentially a mathematical universe where certain types of logic behave perfectly.

06:09.160 --> 06:17.260
A pre-chief topos is a specific fabric of this universe where you can smoothly glue localized observations together to make global sense.

06:17.260 --> 06:18.380
You glue them together.

06:18.580 --> 06:19.800
Yeah, imagine a weather map.

06:20.340 --> 06:25.620
You have local weather stations' bubbles, essentially measuring temperature and pressure in isolated areas.

06:25.740 --> 06:25.920
Right.

06:26.180 --> 06:39.380
The pre-chief topos is the underlying mathematical structure that allows you to seamlessly overlap all those isolated local bubbles into one coherent global weather system without them contradicting each other.

06:39.380 --> 06:40.860
Oh, I see the elegance there.

06:40.940 --> 06:41.520
That makes sense.

06:41.700 --> 06:41.820
Yeah.

06:41.840 --> 06:42.960
But let me push back for a second.

06:43.200 --> 06:43.720
Go for it.

06:43.840 --> 06:54.320
If this just mimics Alonzo Church's old lambda calculus from the 1930s, aren't we just slapping a fancy 3D visualization onto math that already exists?

06:54.840 --> 06:57.540
I mean, a weather map looks nice, but it doesn't change the weather.

06:57.900 --> 07:02.760
What can this geometric foam actually do that my old school Python script can't?

07:02.800 --> 07:03.880
That is the perfect question.

07:03.880 --> 07:06.880
If spherepop were merely a visual skin, it would just be a toy.

07:07.880 --> 07:17.280
Where it radically departs from classical text-based programming is in its native ability to handle the chaotic, parallel, and probabilistic nature of the real world.

07:17.520 --> 07:18.860
Okay, you have my attention.

07:19.060 --> 07:23.140
Traditional lambda calculus is inherently sequential and deterministic.

07:23.580 --> 07:25.680
One domino falls, then the next.

07:25.680 --> 07:34.420
First, spherepop introduces two entirely new core geometric primitives to break that limitation, and they are merge and choice.

07:35.060 --> 07:42.580
Wait, but in traditional coding, making two things happen at exactly the same time like concurrency usually results in a crash if they bump into each other.

07:42.960 --> 07:47.680
How does spherepop's geometry prevent that collision when merging?

07:47.680 --> 07:51.380
Well, merge acts as parallel or disjunctive composition.

07:51.880 --> 07:54.140
Mathematically, it functions like a categorical tensor.

07:54.140 --> 07:58.940
It allows two completely independent processes to run alongside each other in the foam.

07:59.260 --> 07:59.680
Without crashing.

07:59.840 --> 08:00.340
Without crashing.

08:00.680 --> 08:03.760
Because it's geometric, it's both associative and commutative.

08:03.920 --> 08:04.080
Yeah.

08:04.160 --> 08:07.120
It literally doesn't matter what order you merge the bubbles in.

08:07.360 --> 08:15.020
The system naturally handles them as parallel branches of reality operating at once without a central traffic cop dictating who goes first.

08:15.140 --> 08:16.240
Here's where it gets really interesting.

08:16.320 --> 08:16.980
What about choice?

08:17.380 --> 08:19.340
Choice is probabilistic branching.

08:19.340 --> 08:27.880
It allows the program to natively say, take this geometric path with probability P and the other path with probability 1 minus P.

08:28.720 --> 08:33.240
The source material actually connects this to something called the jury distribution monad.

08:33.400 --> 08:35.780
Which means what exactly in physical terms?

08:35.880 --> 08:37.180
Like for the code?

08:37.180 --> 08:47.000
Instead of a program flipping a coin and then acting on the result, the jury monad allows the program to treat the entire probability distribution as a single geometric object.

08:47.160 --> 08:47.840
Wait, what?

08:48.000 --> 08:48.200
Yeah.

08:48.720 --> 08:50.460
Imagine a spinning roulette wheel.

08:50.940 --> 08:57.000
Traditional code waits for the ball to land, reads the number, and then executes the next line based on that number.

08:57.380 --> 08:57.600
Right.

08:57.600 --> 09:07.000
Choice, powered by the jury monad, allows the program to pick up the entire spinning roulette wheel, carry it around, and plug it into other equations before the ball ever lands.

09:07.480 --> 09:09.720
You are doing math with the probabilities themselves.

09:09.980 --> 09:18.900
So wait, if I'm building an app that queries three different independent databases simultaneously, and each database has a slight chance of tining out or failing,

09:18.900 --> 09:23.780
SpherePOP can natively carry those spinning roulette wheels of probability forward?

09:24.100 --> 09:25.680
It does more than carry them.

09:26.040 --> 09:28.140
It aggregates their risk geometrically.

09:28.840 --> 09:33.460
This is codified in a vital theorem from the paper called the Independent Channels Lemma.

09:33.940 --> 09:38.400
It provides a thermodynamic formula for how risk compounds across merged branches.

09:38.520 --> 09:39.460
The DOOM formula.

09:39.580 --> 09:40.900
Exactly, the DOOM formula.

09:40.900 --> 09:52.200
The paper proves that if you have a number of independent channels, and each has a distinct probability of failure, which we can call DOOM, the total probability of systemic DOOM isn't just a simple addition.

09:52.620 --> 09:52.640
Right.

09:52.840 --> 09:59.540
The chance of the entire system failing is one minus the product of the survival probabilities of all the individual channels.

09:59.700 --> 10:09.300
Okay, so I calculate the chance that database A survives, multiply it by the chance database B survives, multiply that by database C, and subtract that whole number from one.

10:09.340 --> 10:09.620
Yes.

10:09.620 --> 10:16.680
That gives me the exact thermodynamic math to calculate the risk of my entire system crashing at any given moment.

10:16.880 --> 10:17.640
That's wild.

10:17.820 --> 10:18.180
It is.

10:18.320 --> 10:20.740
And the philosophical shift here is massive.

10:21.340 --> 10:26.560
Real thought and real-world computation is never a single line of dominoes falling.

10:26.960 --> 10:31.560
It's thousands of branches splitting, calculating probabilities, and merging back together.

10:31.740 --> 10:32.900
Yeah, life isn't sequential.

10:33.200 --> 10:33.520
Right.

10:33.980 --> 10:37.800
Merge and choice allow developers to architect probability natively.

10:37.800 --> 10:42.800
You're engineering the likelihood of outcomes in a concurrent chaotic system.

10:43.020 --> 10:48.240
But, I mean, building these fluid geometric systems only works if things don't constantly bleed into one another.

10:48.400 --> 10:48.700
Sure.

10:48.860 --> 10:56.440
If I have all these probabilistic bubbles splitting and merging all over the place, how do I keep the system from devolving into total nonsense?

10:56.440 --> 11:05.880
Like, if I accidentally merge a bubble that calculates my income tax with a bubble that identifies cat pictures, the system needs a way to protect itself.

11:06.300 --> 11:07.300
There have to be boundaries.

11:07.300 --> 11:13.220
And that necessity leads us directly into the 2026 paper, Types as Refusal Structures.

11:14.080 --> 11:19.600
This paper completely dismantles and redefines what a type is in computer science.

11:19.640 --> 11:22.300
Usually if I think of a type encoding, it's just a label.

11:22.620 --> 11:26.120
Like labeling a variable as an integer or a string of text.

11:26.540 --> 11:28.740
The type checker runs before the program even starts.

11:28.820 --> 11:30.840
Kind of like a spell checker in a word processor.

11:31.040 --> 11:31.260
Right.

11:31.360 --> 11:32.920
Making sure you didn't typo something.

11:33.080 --> 11:33.180
Yeah.

11:33.240 --> 11:35.880
Making sure I didn't try to multiply the word apple by the number four.

11:35.880 --> 11:37.360
Exactly.

11:37.980 --> 11:39.920
Traditional type checking is entirely static.

11:40.320 --> 11:43.040
But in SpherePop, a program isn't just an expression.

11:43.340 --> 11:45.360
It is a physical history of commitments.

11:46.340 --> 11:49.040
The architecture defines four fundamental actions.

11:49.860 --> 11:56.840
Pop to open a scope, refuse to block a path, collapse to commit to a value, and bind to compose operations.

11:57.840 --> 12:01.720
In this framework, a type is redefined as a disciplined refusal structure.

12:02.020 --> 12:04.640
It is an active gatekeeper operating in real time.

12:04.640 --> 12:08.680
It makes me think of an exclusive VIP nightclub.

12:08.740 --> 12:08.980
Okay.

12:09.060 --> 12:09.680
I like this.

12:09.800 --> 12:12.560
The type is the bouncer standing at the door checking IDs.

12:13.000 --> 12:18.800
And the context, the environment of the program, is the history of everyone who has already been admitted to the VIP room.

12:18.800 --> 12:24.420
Let's take that bouncer analogy and make it purely mechanical, because that is how dependent types operate in this calculus.

12:24.980 --> 12:30.120
Specifically, the paper introduces pi types, which are dependent products, and sigma types, dependent sums.

12:30.280 --> 12:30.400
Okay.

12:30.440 --> 12:31.960
How do those mechanical bouncers work?

12:32.220 --> 12:35.060
A pi type acts as a universal repair operator.

12:35.540 --> 12:42.860
It essentially guarantees that no matter what valid history you provide, it possesses a uniform method to safely continue the computation.

12:43.000 --> 12:44.120
It always knows what to do next.

12:44.120 --> 12:44.720
Exactly.

12:45.400 --> 12:48.320
But a sigma type is where the mechanism gets fascinating.

12:48.720 --> 12:49.880
It's a witnessed repair.

12:50.360 --> 12:51.960
It isn't just a bouncer checking a list.

12:52.500 --> 13:01.160
Think of a sigma type as a highly complex physical lock that cannot turn unless the previous key has literally reconfigured the tumblers.

13:01.720 --> 13:02.300
Wait, really?

13:02.300 --> 13:09.080
Yes, the geometry of the first data point, the witness, physically alters the shape of the hole for the next data point.

13:09.220 --> 13:14.880
So the second piece of data's entry entirely depends on the physical presence and shape of the first piece of data.

13:14.980 --> 13:15.400
Exactly.

13:16.080 --> 13:19.780
And this mechanism is how identity types function in SpherePop.

13:20.420 --> 13:22.820
Identity types express controlled substitutability.

13:23.340 --> 13:30.880
They're repair paths proving that one history fragment can seamlessly replace another without violating the physical geometry of the lock.

13:30.880 --> 13:36.700
The paper mentions that this active gatekeeper can return one of three verdicts when evaluating a new piece of data.

13:37.320 --> 13:40.000
It can admit, refuse, or defer.

13:40.380 --> 13:40.680
Right.

13:40.880 --> 13:43.780
Now, I understand admitting data, and I understand refusing data.

13:43.860 --> 13:50.720
Like, if I try to push a cat picture into a math equation, the tumblers don't align, the lock refuses to turn, and that history is permanently blocked.

13:51.040 --> 13:53.360
But I really want to challenge the defer verdict.

13:53.720 --> 13:54.020
Ew.

13:54.540 --> 13:55.600
Why is that?

13:55.600 --> 13:58.540
Why would a computer program ever defer an error?

13:59.300 --> 14:02.820
If something is wrong, shouldn't it just crash or reject it immediately?

14:03.420 --> 14:06.100
Isn't suspending a problem incredibly dangerous?

14:06.620 --> 14:10.020
That touches on the roots of SpherePop and advanced theorem proving.

14:10.020 --> 14:21.000
In a highly complex concurrent system, you frequently encounter situations where the system simply doesn't have enough geometric information yet to know if a continuation is valid.

14:21.160 --> 14:22.420
Because it's running in parallel.

14:22.420 --> 14:22.900
Right.

14:23.380 --> 14:25.380
The other branches haven't merged in yet.

14:25.900 --> 14:28.580
In traditional languages, you're right, the system panics and crashes.

14:28.960 --> 14:32.640
But in an interactive proof state, you want to suspend that obligation.

14:32.840 --> 14:34.560
Like putting the data in a holding pattern.

14:34.660 --> 14:35.120
Exactly.

14:35.340 --> 14:42.040
The lock basically says, I cannot turn right now because the first key hasn't arrived from the other side of the system, but I'm not ejecting you.

14:42.680 --> 14:48.000
Remain in this suspended state and we'll evaluate the geometry again once the missing history is supplied.

14:48.180 --> 14:48.760
Oh, wow.

14:48.760 --> 14:57.980
It allows for open histories and the ecological development of proofs over time rather than demanding the entire universe be solved before the very first step is taken.

14:58.340 --> 15:00.400
But what happens when that lock never turns?

15:00.860 --> 15:03.120
When those boundaries become absolute walls?

15:03.600 --> 15:11.140
We've established that a healthy geometric system needs these active refusals, but if you lock everything down entirely, the system freezes.

15:11.300 --> 15:11.600
It does.

15:11.600 --> 15:20.060
And this transitions us out of computer syntax and directly into the most contentious debate in modern technology, artificial general intelligence.

15:20.180 --> 15:20.440
Yes.

